rf:pack_affidavit_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "001" ;
    rf:dir "affidavit-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Typed Rust catalog + real executable certify-pipeline logic + reference doc, generated from domain vocabulary for ~/affidavit (crates.io `affidavit` v26.6.22, a cryptographic provenance/receipt engine). Modeled from its README's 'Core Concepts' section: a Receipt is an append-only BLAKE3-chained log of Events, each carrying a Commitment (a BLAKE3 digest of payload data -- payloads themselves are never stored in the receipt). Every CertifyStage/Command triple was hand-verified 2026-07-18 against the actual ~/affidavit README.md on disk (byte-for-byte match, not just 'plausible from prose'), version-pinned via afd:sourceVersion in ontology.ttl. No command-surface enumeration attempted for the other 55 verbs (the README documents 59 canonical verbs total in prose only, no table); this pack covers the receipt data model plus 4 named core verbs, not the full CLI. Generates: (1) src/affidavit_catalog.rs -- reference tables (CERTIFY_STAGES, CORE_VERBS); (2) src/affidavit_certify.rs -- real executable logic: an ontology-order-derived Stage dispatcher (next_stage/is_terminal), plus (round 3, 2026-07-18) two generic domain-independent structural primitives (check_strictly_increasing/check_unique) composed by check_stage() per-stage from the ontology's afd:checksMonotonic/afd:checksUnique boolean facts -- check_continuity() is now a thin named call into that ontology-driven dispatch rather than one hand-written affidavit-specific body, proven against adversarial duplicate/out-of-order inputs plus the composition/dispatch mechanism itself in tests/affidavit_certify_proof.rs; (3) docs/affidavit_reference.md; (4) src/affidavit_lib_wiring.rs (force:true, plain file -- NOT inject-mode; retargeted off src/lib.rs during round 2's cross-pack verification after two other packs collided writing to that same path in a shared consumer) containing `pub mod affidavit_catalog;`/`pub mod affidavit_certify;`, which the consumer must mount with one `include!(\\" .

rf:pack_anti_llm_cheat_lsp_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "002" ;
    rf:dir "anti-llm-cheat-lsp-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Typed Rust catalog + reference doc, generated from detector-rule vocabulary for ~/anti-llm-cheat-lsp, a process-mining LSP server (built on lsp-max) that detects LLM-generated code smells: victory-claim overclaiming, dead alternative functions, hedge comments, and unsafe/unverified-routing patterns. Modeled from its README's 6-layer detector stack and its 2-row Rule Index table (ANTI-LLM-DEAD-ALT-001, ANTI-LLM-HEDGE-001) -- the README states the full rule set is larger but only tabulates these two, so only these two are modeled as individuals. Round 2 (2026-07-19): generated detector functions were renamed and re-signed to match the real target exactly -- scan_for_dead_alt/scan_for_hedge, both (filepath: &str, content: &str) -> Vec<Observation>, with Observation/AntiLlmDiagnostic field-for-field ports of the target's src/{observations,diagnostics}.rs and evaluate/evaluate_hedge direct ports of dead_alt.rs::evaluate/hedge.rs::evaluate (against a generated, trimmed AntiLlmConfig carrying only the allowed_suppression_paths/is_suppression_allowed slice those two evaluate fns use). scan_for_hedge now compiles the ontology-sourced regex with the real `regex` crate (via a `hedge_re()` OnceLock, matching the target's own) instead of a hand-rolled substring approximation. The strongest fidelity artifact: the target's own #[cfg(test)] mod tests {..} blocks from dead_alt.rs:153-218 and hedge.rs:114-142 (commit a1bc775) are copied into src/anti_llm_cheat_catalog.rs with the sole edit being the enclosing mod identifier (tests -> dead_alt_tests/hedge_tests, since both can't be named `tests` in one file) -- sha256-verified byte-identical to the source with that line excluded -- and pass unmodified (34/34 total, 2026-07-19, fresh scratch consumer, real `ggen sync run` + `cargo test`, exit 0). Also generates a SPARQL-driven data-fidelity proof test (tests/anti_llm_cheat_catalog_proof.rs) plus adversarial behavioral tests for both scan functions. All 4 generated outputs use freeze_policy: checksum: a hand-edit to any generated file is detected and the next `ggen sync run` refuses to clobber it -- live-verified in a scratch consumer (2026-07-19: appending a comment to src/anti_llm_cheat_catalog.rs then re-running sync produced `\"skipped: frozen: freeze_policy=checksum, on-disk content no longer matches ggen's last-recorded checksum (manual edit detected)\"`, not a silent overwrite). The 4th template (anti_llm_cheat_lib_wiring.rs.tmpl) generates a pack-uniquely-named src/anti_llm_cheat_lsp_pack_lib_wiring.rs (never src/lib.rs itself, to avoid the cross-pack lib.rs collision bug found in round 2) and now also declares an inline `pub mod config { .. }` (the trimmed AntiLlmConfig) at the same crate-root scope, since evaluate/evaluate_hedge and the copied reference tests reference `crate::config::AntiLlmConfig` exactly as the target does -- the consumer still adds exactly one `include!(\"anti_llm_cheat_lsp_pack_lib_wiring.rs\");` line to their own lib.rs, once, and that line never needs to change across regens. This reduces but does not eliminate consumer effort (not L5: the include line is still a manual, one-time step; AntiLlmDiagnostic::to_lsp() was deliberately not ported, since it needs the heavy lsp_max::lsp_types dependency for no behavioral gain in a reference-only pack)." .

rf:pack_cargo_cicd_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "003" ;
    rf:dir "cargo-cicd-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Typed Rust catalog + reference doc + inject-mode mod-wiring, generated from a source-audited command-surface vocabulary for ~/cargo-cicd (crates.io `cargo-cicd`, real dependency: clap-noun-verb 26.6.2, confirmed via its Cargo.toml). Reuses packs/clap-noun-verb-pack's cnv: vocabulary (IRI reuse, not re-minted) since cargo-cicd is itself a real clap-noun-verb CLI. Round 2 (2026-07-18) replaced the original README-only transcription with a dated source audit against ~/cargo-cicd v26.7.6 (src/nouns/*.rs) -- 52 commands across 21 nouns, each carrying a cc:sourceFile citation; 9 rows additionally carry cc:targetOntologyConcept linking to cargo-cicd's own real SKOS/PROV-O ontology. Round 3 (2026-07-18) re-read every real `#[verb(...)]`-annotated `pub fn cmd_*` signature in that same source tree and added cc:argCount/cc:args call-metadata facts to all 51 live rows (39 genuinely zero-arg, 12 with real typed argument lists up to doctor-repo's 5) -- this is the first argument/call-metadata fact this pack has ever carried, clearing Ontology expressiveness's L2 bar for the first time. The generated catalog gained two new real functions (parse_args, args_are_consistent) plus 4 new adversarial/consistency proof tests exercising them against every row, not a hand-picked sample. All three regenerable artifacts (catalog, proof, reference doc) switched from force:true to freeze_policy:checksum/freeze_slots_dir -- live-verified in a scratch consumer: a hand-edit to the generated catalog now makes the next `ggen sync run` report 'skipped: frozen: ... manual edit detected' instead of silently clobbering it, while an unedited file still round-trips as 'skipped: unchanged'. cc:doctor-bare is retained, deprecated, for backward compatibility with the pre-audit bare-noun shape. Round 4 (2026-07-19) added the first real error/return-type facts: re-audited ~/cargo-cicd's 21 nouns/*.rs files (grep-confirmed every #[verb] cmd_* returns clap_noun_verb::Result<()>, uniform across all 51 live rows) and cross-referenced the real dependency ~/clap-noun-verb/src/error.rs for the 10 actual #[non_exhaustive] NounVerbError variant names (transcribed verbatim, not paraphrased). Generated catalog gained CARGO_CICD_RETURN_TYPE/CARGO_CICD_ERROR_ENUM/CARGO_CICD_ERROR_VARIANTS constants plus all_commands_share_return_contract(); proof gained 4 new tests (15 total, up from 11) covering exact-count drift, sortedness/dedup, and contract uniformity. Live-verified end-to-end in a scratch consumer (ggen sync run, real cargo test): 15/15 passing. This closes part of Ontology expressiveness/Target-API fidelity's L3 'error cases' gap that Round 3 explicitly left open, but stops short of L3 in full: no per-command error-path (which variant a given command actually raises) or exit-code facts are modeled -- only the shared enum-level contract, uniform across all rows." .

rf:pack_chicago_tdd_tools_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "004" ;
    rf:dir "chicago-tdd-tools-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.3.0" ;
    rf:description "Generates CliHarness-based Chicago-style CLI boundary tests (#[test] fns crossing a real binary boundary) from ctt:CliBoundaryTest individuals, dispatching through one reusable generated module (tests/chicago_tdd_tools_boundary_runtime.rs, from cli_boundary_runtime.rs.tmpl) that defines the real run_boundary_spec(spec) -> Result<(), String> dispatch function (parse BoundarySpec -> dispatch via CliHarness -> emit Result) instead of duplicating CliHarness-spawn-and-assert logic per generated test. Also generates its own proof test (tests/chicago_tdd_tools_boundary_proof.rs): since both generated files are still independent Tera+SPARQL renders of the same sparql: tests query (this proof cannot call the OTHER template's render logic in-process), the proof reads the REAL rendered text of both sibling files off disk and asserts the query-derived literals -- fn signatures, BoundarySpec field literals, axiom doc-comments, the include!/dispatch-function/struct definitions, and a 1:1 call-site count -- appear in them verbatim. EXPECTED_TEST_COUNT is tests | length at render time, not a hardcoded literal." .

rf:pack_clap_noun_verb_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "005" ;
    rf:dir "clap-noun-verb-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Generates clap-noun-verb route skeletons (noun-verb #[verb] fns calling handler stubs) from cnv:Command individuals in the pack ontology. Commands carrying cnv:staticResponse render their entire body inline from the ontology literal and require ZERO hand-written crate::verbs::handlers::* fn (see cnv:SessionPing) -- all other commands still delegate to a hand-written handler seam. cnv:Noun -> cnv:Command is a formal cnv:hasCommand object property, checked by shapes.ttl (cardinality + non-empty required fields on every Command/Noun). The same template also renders a #[cfg(test)] proof module into the end of that same generated routes file (private-fn visibility requires an in-file test mod, not a separate tests/*.rs -- and a second template targeting the same `to:` path would hit this engine's own FM-WRITE-008 duplicate-output guard) asserting real calls through the generated wrappers, actual-content assertions for the zero-handler command, and drift-canary literals rendered from the same commands/nouns SPARQL projection as the routes themselves (not hand-transcribed). Tier 3 (added 2026-07-19) exercises the REAL #[verb]-macro CLI dispatch path per command -- literal argv -> clap parsing -> the linkme-registered noun/verb tree -> the real handler -- via clap_noun_verb::cli::registry::CommandRegistry::get().run(argv), plus a real negative-path test per command with a required argument (clap's own required-arg enforcement failing closed, not a hand-written assertion about what it should do). Verified this MUST stay inside this file's own #[cfg(test)] mod, not a separate tests/*.rs integration-test crate: a separate test binary that references nothing else from the consumer crate never links in the .o containing this file's #[linkme::distributed_slice] registrations, so CommandRegistry::get_all_noun_names() comes back empty there even though the identical call from a unit test (or the real compiled binary) sees both nouns -- confirmed with a throwaway debug probe in both positions before settling on the in-file design." .

rf:pack_claude_code_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "006" ;
    rf:dir "claude-code-pack" ;
    rf:version "26.7.19" ;
    rf:description "Generates Claude Code multi-agent workflow scripts (the Workflow tool's JS harness format: export const meta { name, description, phases } + phase()/agent()/parallel() body) from RDF individuals, mirroring the orchestration structure proven across this repo's own development sessions: parallel implementation fan-out, then a sequential verify agent, with the standing rule that a workflow's own self-report is never accepted as proof (the consumer re-runs the matrix). The ontology models ccw:Workflow -> ccw:Phase -> ccw:AgentJob, with prompts as authored literals (same sourceText discipline as tcps-core-pack). The gate refuses any workflow that lacks a verify phase -- the discipline is law, not convention." .

rf:pack_dogfood_lifecycle_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "007" ;
    rf:dir "dogfood-lifecycle-pack" ;
    rf:version "26.7.13" ;
    rf:description "v26.7.13 Operation Dogfood session-lifecycle schema: the RDF vocabulary, SHACL shape, and sample fixtures for capturing a Claude Code session's tool events (Bash / Edit / Write / Read / Task / ...) as PROV-O provenance so that ggen can validate a session log. A PostToolUse hook appends one Turtle node per tool event and a session-end recipe runs `ggen graph validate --files <session.ttl> --shapes <shapes.ttl>`; this pack authors the vocabulary + shape + fixtures that loop targets (the hook and recipe themselves are wired by the parent session, not here). PUBLIC-ONTOLOGY-FIRST (mirrors packs/soc2-audit-pack and packs/dry-run-publish-pack): every relationship reuses a public vocabulary where one fits — prov: (Activity for the session and each tool event, Agent for the operator and subagents, used/generated/wasAssociatedWith/actedOnBehalfOf), dcterms: (identifier for the session id, isPartOf for the tool-event -> session ref, description), skos: (ConceptScheme + notation for the closed tool-name and outcome vocabularies), time: (inXSDDateTimeStamp for the wall-independent event timestamp). Content-addressed tool inputs/outputs use the repo's existing urn:blake3:<hex> scheme (crates/chatman-common provenance::content_address, crates/cng pipeline.rs ImportedArtifact). DISCLOSED MINTED TERMS (capability-justified, no public equivalent — each carries an rdfs:comment in ontology.ttl naming the checked public ontologies and why they do not fit): dfl:Session and dfl:ToolEvent (rdfs:subClassOf prov:Activity — PROV has no subtype distinguishing a session-scoped activity from a single tool invocation, and SHACL needs a precise sh:targetClass to require tool-event properties without imposing them on the session node); dfl:sequenceIndex (monotonic per-session ordinal — PROV has no event ordinal, OLO's olo:index requires full ordered-list slot membership); dfl:outcome + dfl:Outcome (a tool event's terminal status drawn from a CLOSED 3-value vocab ok/error/blocked — mirrors packs/jira-tracking-pack's closed jira:Status scheme; no public ontology enumerates tool-invocation outcomes). OBSERVATION-ONLY FENCE (structural, not merely stated): this pack MODELS the session lifecycle as observation/provenance; it never asserts authority, permission, or actuation — those are separate governed surfaces (admission, hooks, receipts in crates/praxis-graphlaw/src/chatman). No class, predicate, or individual here is named 'authorize', 'permit', 'grant', 'actuate', or 'execute'; the outcome vocabulary records what a tool event OBSERVABLY did (ok/error/blocked), never that it was permitted to. No external ontology is unioned — this pack's vocabulary is self-contained PROV/DCMI/SKOS/OWL-Time, so no ggen.toml extra_ontologies entry is required. No private namespace is minted beyond the disclosed capability-justified terms above." .

# Four packs admitted 2026-07-20 (were on disk with pack.toml but absent from this
# inventory, leaving the generated Pack Inventory table 4 rows stale vs `ls packs`):
# ggen-constitution-pack, ggen-release-pack, gh-terraform-pack, level-five-book-pack.
# rf:order uses letter-suffixed values (007b/007c/008b/008c) so the lexical ORDER BY
# keeps the table alphabetical without renumbering the 28 existing individuals.
rf:pack_ggen_constitution_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "007b" ;
    rf:dir "ggen-constitution-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "ggen-constitution-pack (heal-thyself-r1): admitted-semantics mirror of .specify/memory/constitution.md v2.0.0. One ccn:Law individual per numbered constitutional principle (I-XIV), each carrying ccn:statement (verbatim/faithful-paraphrase text, canonical Japanese terms kept verbatim per Principle XIII), ccn:enforcedBy (real file:line anchors, grepped 2026-07-19), ccn:provenBy (real test function names, grepped 2026-07-19), and ccn:mechanized (true only where a real enforcing test/gate was found; false with an honest 'pending' note otherwise -- Principle XI/XII self-certification and receipt-epoch laws are honestly false pending the Center 2 receipt-v2-epoch migration, a separate ongoing workflow phase). Generates docs/CONSTITUTION.md (renders every ccn:Law via SPARQL SELECT) plus two SPARQL ASK gates: every law must carry a statement, and mechanized=true laws must carry a provenBy. Per Principle XI's Governance section: where this pack and .specify/memory/constitution.md's prose disagree, the disagreement is itself a defect -- neither silently wins." .

rf:pack_ggen_release_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "007c" ;
    rf:dir "ggen-release-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Release-engineering surface for ggen itself: a GitHub Actions candidate-publish workflow (.github/workflows/publish-candidate.yml, push:[main] trigger only, never schedule/cron) that chains verify-tcps, docs-sync drift check, book gates, the three existing scripts/ci guard scripts (guard-pack-proofs, guard-claims-schema/guard-publish-standing schema-only, guard-publish-standing full/strict), a new version-consistency check across .specify/repo-facts.ttl / Cargo.toml / ggen.toml, and — only on all-green — a v$VERSION tag push that fires the existing tags-only .github/workflows/release.yml. Also generates an honest RELEASE_STANDING.json/.md pair for ggen (source_standing believable/claimed, binary_standing unverified-on-artifact-host, l5_publication_claim WITHHELD) and docs/PUBLICATION_JUDGMENT.md, a per-condition status table transcribed from GGEN-v26.7.20-製品要求書・構成設計書.md's 第二十九章 公開可能条件 (23 conditions), driven from ontology individuals (grp:CiWorkflow/grp:ReleaseArtifact) whose body literals are the real, byte-for-byte content this pack renders — following the literal-template-body pattern of packs/tcps-release-pack" .

rf:pack_ggen_verify_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "008" ;
    rf:dir "ggen-verify-pack" ;
    rf:version "26.7.19" ;
    rf:description "Self-hosted verification gates: makes `ggen sync run` refuse when external check evidence (build/test/clippy/byte-identity results, emitted as ver: facts by a consumer's verify script) is missing, red, or stale. Closes the loop the reflexive-receipts feature opened: verification stops being a hand-run shell matrix and becomes admitted graph facts enforced by the same FM-PACK-013 gate mechanism as every other pack invariant, identically on both graph engines (see crates/ggen-engine/tests/reasoner_independence_e2e.rs). Consumer contract: wire this pack in [packs], add the emitter's output (evidence/checks.ttl) as an [ontology] source, and run the emitter before sync (e.g. `just verify-tcps` = emitter -> sync -> receipt verify). The freshness gate binds evidence to the latest ggenr:Sync receipt, so it requires [law] reflexive = true in the consumer; staleness detection lags one sync by construction (documented in gates/030_evidence_fresh.rq)." .

rf:pack_gh_terraform_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "008b" ;
    rf:dir "gh-terraform-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Generates Terraform GitHub-management config (integrations/github provider, real HCL bodies modeled verbatim on ~/dev/ranchr and ~/dev/beamops) plus a reusable gh CLI shell-script library, all driven from ghtf:/ghcli: RDF individuals whose bodies are real, byte-for-byte content — no engine changes, template files only echo stored literals." .

rf:pack_level_five_book_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "008c" ;
    rf:dir "level-five-book-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Level Five book transcription pack: 366 book:Chapter + 366 book:Listing individuals carrying verbatim book:sourceText, fanned out to book/src/ via two per-row templates (engine per-row `to:` interpolation). ontology.ttl is a mechanical merge of per-chapter fragments; the book source is the law, generated book/src files are the product." .

rf:pack_lsp_max_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "009" ;
    rf:dir "lsp-max-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Generates lsp-max RulePackServer rules/*.toml regex rule-pack files from LintRule individuals in the pack ontology (id, name, severity, pattern, path_globs, exclude_globs, message, rationale, eval_budget -- all ontology-sourced, field-for-field matching the real rule_pack_server.rs::Rule struct, verified 2026-07-18). Also generates its own proof test (rule_pack_proof.rs.tmpl -> tests/lsp_max_rule_pack_proof.rs) that parses the generated TOML/markdown with real toml/regex crates and checks them against literals hand-transcribed from ontology.ttl, including running each rule's pattern against real positive/negative code snippets. shapes.ttl (added 2026-07-19) SHACL-constrains every lm:LintRule field's cardinality/non-emptiness and closes lm:severity/lm:evalBudget to the real string sets rule_pack_server.rs actually recognizes -- run `ggen graph validate --files ontology.ttl --shapes shapes.ttl`." .

rf:pack_ma_case_study_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "010" ;
    rf:dir "ma-case-study-pack" ;
    rf:version "26.7.13" ;
    rf:description "M&A / deal-desk case study vocabulary (ontology.ttl) + SHACL shapes (shapes.ttl) + competency questions (COMPETENCY_QUESTIONS.md), built from a real vocabulary-fit research pass over 10 domain concepts (entity/LEI, ownership percentage, due-diligence disposition, representation-and-warranty exceptions, regulatory filing thresholds, board authorization, shareholder votes, negotiated deal terms/counter-offers, financing conditions, closing/termination status). PUBLIC-ONTOLOGY-FIRST: FIBO (Financial Industry Business Ontology, read directly from the real vendored copy at crates/praxis-graphlaw/ontologies/industry/financial/fibo-master/, file:line cited per term in ontology.ttl's header) supplies a clean or strained public term for 8 of the 10 concepts (fibo-be-le-lei:LEIRegisteredEntity/LegalEntityIdentifier/hasOwnershipPercentage/RelationshipRecord for entity+LEI+ownership; fibo-fnd-agr-ctr:Representation/Warranty/DisclosureProvision/TermSheet/NonBindingTerm/ConditionPrecedent/TerminationProvision for contract clauses; fibo-fnd-agr-agr:Commitment for financing; fibo-cae-ce-act:MergerAcquisition/ActionStatus/RegulatoryAction and fibo-cae-ce-srca:TenderOffer/FormalOffer for the deal event and offers; fibo-be-oac-exec:BoardOfDirectors and fibo-be-oac-cctl:VotingShareholder for governance party roles); OMG Commons (cmns-bauth:Authorization/AuthorizingParty/AuthorizedParty/authorizes/hasAuthorizedParty/hasAuthorizingParty, cmns-rga:RegulatoryReport, cmns-cls:isClassifiedBy) supplies the live terms FIBO's own local Executives.rdf copies are deprecated in favor of; W3C ODRL (odrl:Duty) and PROV-O (prov:Activity/Entity/generatedAtTime/wasAttributedTo) and Dublin Core (dcterms:isPartOf) round out the reuse. Two false friends were checked and explicitly rejected, not silently avoided: fibo-be-le-cb:BoardAgreement (an agreement AMONG directors, not a board's resolution authorizing a transaction) and fibo-fnd-agr-ctr:hasTerm (contract DURATION, not a negotiated deal term). DISCLOSED ma: BRIDGE TERMS (minted only where the research found NO_PUBLIC_TERM_FOUND or a genuine STRAINED_FIT gap, each with an rdfs:comment in ontology.ttl naming the public terms checked and why they don't fit): ma:DueDiligenceItem/DueDiligenceDisposition (a checklist item's open/satisfied/waived status -- no public disposition vocabulary exists), ma:DisclosureScheduleItem/qualifiesClause/scheduleItemNumber (linking a disclosure exception to the specific clause it qualifies), ma:RegulatoryFilingObligation/filingThresholdAmount/triggeringStatute/statutoryWaitingPeriodDays (HSR-Act-style filing threshold and waiting period -- checked and rejected ELI as citation-only and LegalRuleML as a rule-markup language, neither a domain-term source), ma:BoardResolution/authorizesTransaction (a resolution document distinct from the false-friend BoardAgreement), ma:ShareholderVote/Ballot/voteOutcome/VoteOutcome/quorumPercentage/ballotDirection/BallotDirection (no vote/ballot/outcome structure exists in FIBO, W3C ORG, or any other checked candidate), ma:CounterOffer/supersedes/DealTermLineItem/DealTermType/termValue (negotiation-move sequencing and typed deal-term line items layered on TermSheet/NonBindingTerm), ma:FinancingCommitment/FinancingOutCondition/subjectToCondition (an M&A-specific financing-out condition, layered on the generic Commitment/ConditionPrecedent pair), ma:DealStatus + 5 concrete individuals (Signed/PendingRegulatoryApproval/Closed/Terminated/Abandoned instantiating FIBO's otherwise-abstract, zero-individual ActionStatus class). ontology.ttl is a TBox-only vocabulary pack (classes + properties + closed enumerations, mirroring packs/jira-tracking-pack and packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack's own ontology.ttl shape); shapes.ttl applies sh:closed only to this pack's own minted ma: classes (open floor shapes for reused FIBO/Commons classes, matching packs/soc2-audit-pack's own org:Organization precedent). No external ontology file is unioned via ggen.toml extra_ontologies; every FIBO/Commons/ODRL/PROV/DCMI term is reused directly by IRI, never re-vendored or re-serialized into this pack. A LATER PASS (fixtures/, DESIGN.md) added a concrete Meridian Holdings Group / Corvantis Systems Acquirer/Target instance-data scenario across all 6 independent M&A processes docs/releases/v26.7.14/THESIS.md Section 33.12 names (buyer diligence, seller disclosure, financing, regulatory review, board authority, shareholder action), plus fixtures/hook.ttl (a real kh:Hook deriving an HSR-Act-style regulatory filing obligation, proven live by crates/praxis-graphlaw/tests/ma_case_hook_actuation.rs) and the adversarial-positive.ttl/adversarial-negative.ttl G_x+/G_x- pair Section 33.11's semantic admission proof obligation names; see DESIGN.md for the full account." .

rf:pack_mcpp_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "011" ;
    rf:dir "mcpp-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Typed Rust catalog + subprocess dispatch shim + reference doc, generated from command-surface vocabulary for ~/mcpp (MCP+ admissible-work runtime, real dependency: clap-noun-verb = \"5\", confirmed via its Cargo.toml). Reuses packs/clap-noun-verb-pack's cnv: vocabulary (IRI reuse), including cnv:args for real argument facts. The 9 commands were originally grepped from ~/mcpp/README.md, then hand-verified on 2026-07-18 against the real #[verb] function signatures at pinned commit ae1106887a824f107dc8ac76daff6ef1b8dbf6c4 (see ontology.ttl's header for file:line citations) -- that pass found and fixed one real fidelity bug (relay's real verb is 'verify-chain', not 'verify'). Still a partial command surface: these 9 are not every #[verb] in ~/mcpp/crates/mcpp-server/src/cmds/. Generates: src/mcpp_catalog.rs (typed noun/verb/doc/args/error_case table), src/mcpp_dispatch.rs (a real, compilable, ontology-driven std::process::Command dispatch shim -- one generated wrapper fn per command, no hand-written handler required), docs/mcpp_reference.md, a pack-uniquely-named src/mcpp_lib_wiring.rs mod-aggregator (the consumer adds one `include!(\"mcpp_lib_wiring.rs\");` line to their own src/lib.rs -- retargeted off `to: src/lib.rs`/`inject: true` after round 2's cross-pack verification found that pattern collides via this engine's FM-WRITE-008 guard the moment 2 packs sharing it are wired into one real consumer), tests/mcpp_catalog_proof.rs (hand-transcribed, non-tautological data-table proof, now also asserting a per-row error_case is present and spot-checking its exact text) and tests/mcpp_dispatch_proof.rs (real behavior proof: introspects the actual std::process::Command built by each generated wrapper, plus two real error-path tests that spawn a nonexistent `mcpp` binary and assert on the genuine std::io::ErrorKind::NotFound -- not a mock). Round 3 (2026-07-18) added mcp:errorCase: a real, file:line-cited non-zero-exit/fail-open condition for all 9 commands read directly from the same pinned commit's source, closing the second half of the ontology-expressiveness L3 bar (cnv:args covered structure/cardinality in round 2; error cases were the missing half). All generated outputs use freeze_policy=checksum (not force:true): a hand-edit to a generated file is detected and the next sync skips it with an explicit 'manual edit detected' receipt entry instead of silently clobbering it -- re-verified this round against the modified templates. Round 4 (2026-07-19) added shapes.ttl: real SHACL constraints on cnv:Command (non-empty noun/verb, a well-formed cnv:args grammar, and a non-empty, non-placeholder mcp:errorCase) wired via a consumer's [law].shapes -- confirmed live in a scratch consumer: the real ontology passes ggen sync run's validate stage, and a deliberately-broken copy (one mcp:errorCase triple removed) is refused with a real FM-LAW-013 SHACL violation citing the exact focus node, not a no-op gate." .

rf:pack_mfact_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "012" ;
    rf:dir "mfact-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Typed Rust catalog + reference doc, generated from domain vocabulary for ~/mfact (README title: 'mfact / procint'), a receipted mathematical-manufacturing pipeline where ggen itself projects a Lean 4 declaration catalog that Lean admits and mfact certifies -- a real, in-the-wild downstream consumer of ggen, not merely an analogous project. Modeled from its README: the 3-actor pipeline (ggen projects -> Lean admits -> mfact certifies) and its 5 top-level authority directories (packs/, procint/, paper/, release/, .mfact/artifacts.toml). Also generates its own anti-drift proof test (tests/mfact_catalog_proof.rs) asserting the rendered catalog against literal values hand-transcribed from ontology.ttl." .

rf:pack_mfw_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "013" ;
    rf:dir "mfw-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Typed Rust catalog + reference doc + real transition-dispatch logic, generated from domain vocabulary for ~/mfw (MFW monorepo), a receipted process-consequence system. Modeled from its AGENTS.md: the 10-stage observe->admit->preserve standing->calculate residual->manufacture candidate->verify->authorize->actuate->receipt->replay cycle (asserted as explicit mfw:nextStage graph edges, not just an mfw:order integer), and its 9 top-level authority-surface directories (ontology/, profiles/, transform/, mfw-theory/, runtime/, verifier/, fixtures/, docs/, receipts/) -- each now also carrying a real mfw:standingAuthority boolean per ~/mfw/AGENTS.md's own law (docs/ is the one surface that never carries standing authority; every other surface does), driving a generated is_standing_authority(path) dispatch function rather than a hardcoded Rust special case. No per-crate description fields were populated in mfw-runtime/mfw-meaning/mfw-powl-miner/mfw-shacl's own Cargo.toml files (confirmed empty this pass), so those 4 workspace crates are named but not further characterized here. Generates real next_stage()/is_valid_transition()/is_standing_authority() dispatch driven entirely by ontology data (not hardcoded arithmetic or string comparisons), plus a self-check test module embedded directly in the generated catalog (mfw_catalog.rs.tmpl) whose expected counts -- including a non-standing-authority count -- come from independently-shaped SPARQL COUNT(...) aggregate queries, catching catalog/ontology drift on every `cargo test` without a human re-transcription step for those counts. The separate templates/mfw_catalog_proof.rs.tmpl proof (-> tests/mfw_catalog_proof.rs) remains additionally hand-transcribed against the ontology for the row-content spot checks (not just counts, now including the standing-authority rule spot check), and templates/mfw_catalog_mod_wiring.rs.tmpl writes `pub mod mfw_catalog;` to a pack-unique file (src/mfw_lib_wiring.rs, force:true) rather than injecting into the consumer's shared src/lib.rs -- that retarget (this pack originally targeted src/lib.rs with inject:true) was required once a real multi-pack consumer wired 2 packs doing the same thing and hit this engine's FM-WRITE-008 duplicate-output guard; the consumer must add one `include!(\"mfw_lib_wiring.rs\");` line to their own src/lib.rs, a real, disclosed remaining consumer-effort step, not zero. The ontology also carries a machine-readable mfw:SourceSnapshot (exact ~/mfw commit hash + date this pack was transcribed from) instead of only a prose claim -- ~/mfw remains a separate repository this workspace does not own, so its RDF cannot be imported directly as a live dependency." .

rf:pack_osx_clnr_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "014" ;
    rf:dir "osx-clnr-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.1.0" ;
    rf:description "Typed Rust catalog + real selection/parsing logic + a generated dispatch layer + reference doc, generated from domain vocabulary for ~/osx-clnr (a real local project, crates.io-bound `oclnr`, a plan-bound macOS disk auditor; real dependency: clap-noun-verb 26.6.2). Unlike cargo-cicd/mcpp, its README documents the pipeline in prose rather than a command table, so this pack models the pipeline's real nouns (audit -> plan -> delete -> receipt, plus snapshot/emergency) as oclnr:Stage individuals with real state-transition (`oclnr:nextStage`) edges, plus per-command `oclnr:Argument` structure (name/type/required/default/position) and a `oclnr:SnapshotSelectionPolicy`/`oclnr:ByteUnit` fact set -- all dated hand-verified 2026-07-18 directly against ~/osx-clnr's real source (src/nouns/{snapshot,receipt,emergency}.rs, src/domain/time.rs), not README/grep guessing. `templates/osx_clnr_plan.rs.tmpl` generates a REAL, compilable reimplementation of `~/osx-clnr`'s snapshot-selection and byte-size-parsing algorithm (`select_oldest_snapshots`/`parse_snapshot_date`/`parse_size_in_bytes`), with its unit table and date-suffix-length parameter SPARQL-derived from the ontology rather than hardcoded in the template. `templates/osx_clnr_dispatch.rs.tmpl` (round 3) closes part of the handler-gap: a new `oclnr:dispatchesTo` fact per `cnv:Command` names the real `osx_clnr_plan.rs` function that implements it (2 of 5 commands today), or the empty string if none is modeled yet; the template reads that fact to emit either a fully generated handler (zero hand-write) or a method on a generated `OclnrHandlerSeam` trait (the stable hand-write seam for the other 3) -- which commands land in which bucket is ontology-driven, not template-hardcoded. `templates/osx_clnr_mod_wiring.rs.tmpl` does NOT target the consumer's `src/lib.rs` directly (an earlier design that used `inject: true` there was retargeted after round-2 cross-pack verification found it collides with this engine's FM-WRITE-008 duplicate-output guard the moment a second pack does the same thing in one real consumer, e.g. wasm4pm-cognition-pack + wasm4pm-facts-pack in examples/receiptctl): it generates a pack-unique `src/osx_clnr_lib_wiring.rs` that the consumer mounts with one `include!(\"osx_clnr_lib_wiring.rs\");` line in their own `src/lib.rs` -- a real, disclosed, non-zero consumer-effort step, not 'wires ggen.toml, done'. Three proof suites ship: `osx_clnr_catalog_proof.rs.tmpl` (deliberately non-SPARQL, hand-transcribed anti-drift check on the reference catalog), `osx_clnr_plan_proof.rs.tmpl` (SPARQL-derived cardinality assertion + 13 behavioral tests against the real generated logic, including adversarial/error-path cases: empty input, unknown unit, garbage snapshot names, n=0, n larger than available), and `osx_clnr_dispatch_proof.rs.tmpl` (5 tests: 2 real generated handlers exercised including an adversarial rejection path, plus a dummy `OclnrHandlerSeam` impl proving the generated trait is real, compilable, callable Rust). L5-push round (2026-07-19): `osx_clnr_plan.rs.tmpl` gained `identify_thinned_snapshots`/`SnapshotThinReceipt`, transcribed field-for-field from `~/osx-clnr/src/domain/time.rs` (source-verified 2026-07-19; these two have no free ontology parameter, so unlike the unit table/date-suffix-length they are named individuals in `ontology.ttl` but their bodies are hand-transcribed, honestly documented as such rather than dressed up as SPARQL-driven). Two new templates, `osx_clnr_domain_time.rs.tmpl` (`src/domain/time.rs`, a `pub use crate::osx_clnr_plan::*;` re-export shim) and `osx_clnr_domain_mod.rs.tmpl` (`src/domain/mod.rs`), exist so a consumer crate literally packaged as `osx_clnr` exposes `osx_clnr::domain::time::*` at the SAME module path as the real reference -- which is what let `reference/verbatim_time_tests.rs` (the reference's own `test_snapshot_query_thin_parsing`/`test_size_parsing`, copied byte-identical from `~/osx-clnr/tests/integration_tests.rs`, checksum `14c560f1...5a61dd` before and after copy) compile and pass with ZERO modification, including its unedited `use osx_clnr::domain::time::{...}` import lines, against fully ontology-generated code -- verified live in a scratch consumer (`cargo test`: 32 passed, 0 failed, exit 0), not asserted from prose." .

rf:pack_praxis_core_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "015" ;
    rf:dir "praxis-core-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.3.0" ;
    rf:description "praxis-core pack: generates the refusal-taxonomy reference table (Rust const table + markdown doc) from RefusalScenario individuals mirroring praxis_core::refusal. Also generates a proof test (tests/praxis_core_refusal_taxonomy_proof.rs) that checks the two artifacts against literal, hand-transcribed values from ontology.ttl -- no SPARQL re-derivation. L5-push round 3 (2026-07-19): switched the two primary generated artifacts (src/praxis_core_refusal_table.rs, docs/praxis_core_refusal_taxonomy.md) from force:true to freeze_policy:checksum (freeze_slots_dir: .ggen/freeze/praxis-core-pack) -- a hand-edit is now refused with a named checksum-mismatch error on the next sync instead of silently clobbered; verified live in a scratch consumer (edit -> refused; delete freeze cache -> falls back to FM-WRITE-005 hard refusal, not silent overwrite either way). Also implemented, for real, the `cfg(feature = \"praxis-core-live\")` compiled-fidelity block the proof template's docstring had claimed but never shipped: when a consumer depends on the real `praxis-core` crate and enables that feature, the generated proof now calls the REAL `RefusalScenario::category()` for all 13 variants and asserts agreement with this pack's generated table -- verified live (10/10 tests pass with the feature enabled via a path dependency in a scratch consumer; 8/8 pass without it, so the default path is unaffected). L5-push round 4 (2026-07-19): added templates/refusal_verbatim_reference_tests.rs.tmpl, generating tests/praxis_core_refusal_verbatim_reference_tests.rs -- a BYTE-IDENTICAL copy (checksummed sha256 30c0d52c...be24e2e0 before and after pasting, diff-verified against the extracted source) of the real #[cfg(test)] mod tests block from crates/praxis-core/src/refusal.rs lines 252-367 (the reference author's own 4 unit tests: category_mapping_is_total_over_obligations, category_mapping_is_total_over_denial_lanes, kernel_and_andon_scenarios_have_expected_categories, compose_denials_ors_lanes), gated behind #![cfg(feature = \"praxis-core-live\")] as a whole-file cfg so it contributes zero tests/compile cost when the consumer doesn't opt in. Verified live in a rebuilt scratch consumer with a direct optional dependency on both praxis-core (path) and bcinr-powl-receipt = \"26.6.24\" (required for the verbatim block's own `use bcinr_powl_receipt::denial::DenialPolarity`, which is not re-exported by praxis-core): cargo test feature-off is 8/8 passing (unaffected, new file compiles to 0 tests); cargo test --features praxis-core-live is 14/14 passing (10 existing + 4 verbatim reference tests, all green, 0 failures). This is the reference's OWN test suite recompiled and run here, not a new assertion informed by reading the source -- the strongest fidelity signal this pack can produce short of depending on praxis-core's own `cargo test` output directly. Honest scope: still opt-in (a consumer must discover and enable the feature) and not wired into this repo's CI/pre-commit, so this does not clear L4's 'the normal way' bar or L5's 'zero human in the loop' bar -- it strengthens Target-API fidelity within L3, it does not move the pack to L4/L5." .

rf:pack_self_monitoring_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "016" ;
    rf:dir "self-monitoring-pack" ;
    rf:version "26.7.13" ;
    rf:description "Self-monitoring vocabulary + real Knowledge Hook for Claude Code's own answer-format pattern, dogfooding the EXACT kh:Hook SPARQL-CONSTRUCT mechanism already proven this session for the Solvane Global bribery case's obligation derivation (crates/multifractal-workflow/fixtures/bribery-case/hook.ttl + crates/multifractal-workflow/tests/bribery_case_fixture.rs), applied here to conversational turns instead of compliance cases. PUBLIC-ONTOLOGY-FIRST (mirrors packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack and the bribery-case fixture): a conversational turn is a prov:Activity (smon:Turn, minted subclass -- PROV has no such subtype), the session reference reuses dcterms:isPartOf pointed at packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack's OWN dfl:Session class (no re-minted smon:Session -- this is the IRI-reuse-across-files discipline applied at the vocabulary layer), the grounding_topic tag reuses dcterms:subject directly (checked and fits -- \"the topic of the resource\" is exactly \"which system/capability this turn concerns\", no bridge term needed), and turn-kind is a CLOSED 5-concept SKOS scheme (smon:GroundingQuestion / smon:SurveyResponse / smon:RunResponse / smon:BlockerResponse / smon:Other) mirroring dfl:Outcome's identical closed-scheme pattern. DISCLOSED MINTED TERMS (capability-justified, no public equivalent -- each carries an rdfs:comment in ontology.ttl naming the checked public ontologies and why they do not fit): smon:Turn (prov:Activity subclass), smon:sequenceIndex (mirrors dfl:sequenceIndex's identical rationale, domain-scoped), smon:immediatelyFollows (a direct turn-adjacency edge minted specifically because this session confirmed, by reading crates/praxis-graphlaw/src/sparql/plan.rs::extract_expression, that Expression::Add/Subtract are NOT implemented in this engine -- so \"the turn immediately after X\" is expressed as a graph-pattern join, never SPARQL arithmetic), smon:turnKind + smon:TurnKind (closed classification, mirrors dfl:outcome), smon:EscalationObligation + smon:hasPriorGroundingQuestion + smon:hasGroundingQuestion + smon:reason (the derived-fact node hook.ttl's kh:Hook CONSTRUCT query produces -- PROV's wasDerivedFrom/wasInformedBy checked and rejected on a genuine Entity-vs-Activity domain/range mismatch, not just unfashionable). CLASSIFICATION-IS-INPUT FENCE (structural, not merely stated): hook.ttl's SPARQL CONSTRUCT query only ever READS smon:turnKind, dcterms:subject, smon:sequenceIndex, and smon:immediatelyFollows -- every one of those is a fixture-hand-asserted INPUT fact; the hook never reads turn TEXT (no turn-content literal is even modeled in this vocabulary) and never classifies anything. Building an NLP classifier that reads raw Claude Code output and assigns smon:turnKind is a separate, explicitly out-of-scope problem this pack does not attempt or stub. Real live SPARQL-CONSTRUCT verification (not asserted): crates/praxis-graphlaw/tests/self_monitoring_hook_actuation.rs runs the real praxis_graphlaw::TripleStore::load_hook_pack + .materialize() + .query() pipeline against fixtures/pattern-fires.ttl (fires, derives exactly 1 smon:EscalationObligation), fixtures/pattern-does-not-fire.ttl (does not fire -- prior response was a RunResponse, not a SurveyResponse), and fixtures/pattern-different-topic.ttl (does not fire -- same_system/grounding_topic conjunct fails)." .

rf:pack_star_toml_pack a rf:Pack ;
    rf:order "017" ;
    rf:dir "star-toml-pack" ;
    rf:version "0.3.0" ;
    rf:description "Generates a star_toml config-admission module: serde structs per ConfigSection (closed-world/loader/optionality projected from stp:closedWorld/stp:loaderFn/stp:required ontology facts, not hardcoded in the template), plus a generated validate() method per section projecting stp:minValue/stp:maxValue behavior-contract facts (a pre-condition on the admitted VALUE that serde's Deserialize cannot express -- e.g. sample_rate must be in [0.0, 1.0]), plus per-section admission docs and a Cargo.toml dependency snippet doc (docs/star_toml/CARGO_DEPENDENCIES.md, from stp:cargoDependency). Ships src/star_toml_lib_wiring.rs (pack-unique file, one include!() line needed in the consumer's own lib.rs -- NOT inject:true into src/lib.rs directly, after round-2 cross-pack verification found that pattern collides the moment two packs are wired into the same real consumer). Also generates its own executable proof test (tests/star_toml_config_proof.rs, no sparql: frontmatter) that hardcodes the ontology's section/field literals independently and exercises the real load_file round-trip, the stp:required=false optional-field path, the stp:minValue/stp:maxValue behavior-contract path (both an out-of-range value that parses but fails validate(), and an in-range value that passes), plus three fail-closed paths (unknown key, missing required field, missing file) against real TempDir-backed TOML files. Both generated-source templates use freeze_policy: checksum (not force: true) so a hand-edited output is refused, not silently overwritten, on the next sync." .

